7 Related Work
Semantic caching.
GPTCache [2] and CacheBlend [20] reduce LLM API cost by embedding-similarity retrieval. Neither stores the capability configuration under which an answer was generated, so neither provides a safety guarantee on cache hits. The CAS uses embeddings only as a computational pre-filter; correctness is grounded in formal containment. The PAB pre-computes structured follow-up answers at write time, eliminating cache misses on structurally predictable follow-ups.
Knowledge graph-augmented RAG.
Belief state tracking vs. session closure.
Task-oriented dialogue systems maintain a belief state—a running estimate of user intent—across turns. State-of-the-art trackers include TRADE [18], SimpleTOD [10], and TripPy [9], all benchmarked on MultiWOZ. The critical distinction is that belief state tracking is a prediction problem—given utterances, infer the current slot-value configuration—while session closure is a reachability problem—given the current slot-value configuration, certify what the system can derive. These are orthogonal: any belief state tracker can serve as the function feeding session closure. In the MultiWOZ experiment, ground-truth belief states decouple the two problems; the effect of tracker error on safety certification is Open Problem 9.
Proactive dialogue.
Proactive dialogue systems [15, 19] anticipate follow-up needs using learned conversation flow models. The PAB is formally derived from the closure, not learned, and every pre-answer carries a safety certificate. The near-miss frontier provides a proactive suggestion grounded in the hypergraph structure rather than statistical co-occurrence.
Tool-augmented LLMs and formal safety.
Toolformer [14], ToolLLM [13], and ReAct [21] activate capabilities dynamically but do not model capability interactions formally. The hypergraph framework provides the missing structure: hyperarcs encode conjunctive dependencies between tools determining what the composed system can reach—which these systems cannot certify. Assume-guarantee reasoning [12] and contract-based design [3] verify fixed compositions post-hoc; Theorem 2.1 proves that no component-level verification can replace the pre-execution gate for conjunctive capability systems.
8 Empirical Results
What these experiments are and are not.
The evaluation on MultiWOZ 2.2 is a controlled validation of the formal model, not a deployment claim. MultiWOZ is chosen precisely because its ground-truth belief state annotations make the Completeness Assumption verifiable by construction: every capability the pipeline activates is known to be in . This lets us test the formal guarantees without confounding from tracker error. The formal theorems (Pipeline Safety, Cache Soundness, Session Cost) are validated by checking their predictions against the measured data. The NatCS experiment in Appendix B is the protocol for repeating this validation under estimated, imperfect belief states.
8.1 Dataset, Extraction, and Mapping
We use the MultiWOZ 2.2 test split (1,000 dialogues, 13,965 turns). Algorithm 1 at on the training split yields the hypergraph summarized in Table 1. The forbidden set encodes the requirement that bookings not be confirmed without a verified candidates-retrieved step. The TemplateDB contains 28 templates (65.1% of 43 nodes); we additionally evaluate at 25%, 50%, and 75% synthetic coverage.
8.2 Results
Analysis.
Three findings validate the framework. First, mean RAG calls matches the Session Cost Theorem prediction to within rounding on real human-generated dialogue, providing independent validation of the formal model. Second, PAB hit rate degrades gracefully with coverage: even at , 36.1% of turns are served without RAG (10.5 reduction from baseline). Third, 143 unsafe cosine cache hits (14.3%) arise from cross-domain contamination: restaurant and hotel answers share similar surface strings but incompatible capability sets. All 143 are caught by the CAS containment check; none by the cosine cache. This is the concrete MultiWOZ instantiation of Theorem 6.3. The hypergraph planner produces zero AND-violations across all 13,965 turns, consistent with Theorem 3.1.
Assumptions as testable predictions.
The paper’s guarantees rest on three assumptions; we frame each as a falsifiable prediction with a corresponding test.
(1) Completeness of : every capability the pipeline activates is in . In MultiWOZ this holds by construction. Prediction: under random slot omission (simulating a tracker with recall ), safety violation rate remains below for , because omitting a slot is more likely to block a conjunctive arc than to open a path toward . This is the -incompleteness experiment of Appendix A. The structural argument: is reached only through the booking arc, which requires all of its preconditions; omitting any one precondition blocks the arc entirely.
(2) Correctness of : the forbidden set accurately specifies what must not be activated. This is a specification assumption, not an empirical one. It cannot be validated by experiment; it must be verified by the system designer at deployment. We make no claim that our particular is comprehensive for all deployment contexts.
(3) Correctness of : the extracted hypergraph accurately captures the dependency structure. Prediction: every arc retained by Algorithm 1 at has a true derivation rate above with probability (Theorem 3.2). The extracted arcs’ minimum observed rate of is above threshold, consistent with a true rate comfortably above for all 34 arcs.
Resilience to real-world violations.
Two reviewer concerns are directly addressed by existing results. Tool failures and permission revocation are handled by Theorem 10.1 (Section 10): when a capability is revoked mid-session, the correct session closure is recovered at cost , PAB entries with affected witnesses are invalidated in , and the safety invariant is restored by re-running Stage 3 on the post-revocation capability set. Recovery cost is bounded independently of session length; the worst case equals the no-cache baseline. Evaluation cleanliness: MultiWOZ provides the cleanest available test of the formal model because ground-truth belief states verify the Completeness Assumption by construction. Appendix B provides the experimental protocol for validating the framework on NatCS [8], a public customer service corpus where belief states must be estimated rather than read from annotations.
Scope of safety claims.
The “zero safety regressions” and “zero unsafe hits” results are defined relative to the paper’s formal model: the capability hypergraph , the forbidden set , and the witness containment condition. They establish internal consistency of the safety gate within that formalization. They do not claim robustness to prompt injection attacks on the LLM generation step, malformed ontology extraction producing an incorrect , stale permissions not reflected in the belief state, incorrect state tracking by the function, or adversarial manipulation of tool invocation logs. These are important operational safety concerns beyond the formal model; we treat them as out of scope for this paper and list tracker error propagation and ontology extraction quality as open problems in §9. The formal guarantees are exactly as strong as the Completeness Assumption (Definition 3.1) and the accuracy of as a specification of forbidden capabilities.
9 Open Problems
Tracker error propagation.
In MultiWOZ, is complete by construction. In deployment, is produced by a learned belief state tracker. A formal bound on safety degradation as a function of tracker recall is open; the natural approach models tracker errors as random perturbations of the true belief state and derives PAC-style bounds.
Generalizing Algorithm 1.
Algorithm 1 is specified for task-oriented dialogue ontologies with belief state annotations. Generalizing to arbitrary tool-calling schemas (OpenAI function calling, Anthropic tool use) requires a tool-invocation-log co-occurrence model. The soundness theorem generalizes straightforwardly, but the noise model for tool logs differs from belief state transitions.
NMF pre-fetch under empirical priors.
The pre-fetch guarantee holds under a uniform prior. A Bayesian extension using empirical conversation priors (learned from training data) is a weighted submodular maximization problem for which tighter bounds are open.
Tightening the hit rate bound.
Multi-session persistence.
Persistent session closures for returning users, combined with dynamic expansion between sessions, require incremental invalidation integrated with DRed maintenance. The refined invalidation condition is sound by Theorem 4.1 but cascade-free invalidation is open.
10 Graceful Degradation Under Monotonicity Failure
The Monotonicity Assumption (Definition 2.1) holds within a single planning horizon where capabilities are persistent. Real deployments violate this at session boundaries (token expiry, tool deregistration, permission revocation) and occasionally mid-session (authentication timeouts, tool failures). This section proves that Monotonicity failure is recoverable at bounded cost, converting a fragility into a controlled degradation property.
Definition 10.1 (Revocation Event).
A revocation event at turn removes a set of capabilities from the session closure. The post-revocation session capability set is , and the post-revocation session closure is .
Theorem 10.1 (Graceful Degradation).
Let a revocation event remove at turn . Then:
-
(i)
Recovery cost. The correct post-revocation session closure is computed by a full re-initialization of the closure from at cost , independent of session length.
-
(ii)
PAB invalidation. Any PAB entry with must be invalidated. Invalidation is checkable in by scanning witness sets. Entries with remain valid.
-
(iii)
CAS containment. The CAS lookup condition remains correct after re-initialization: only entries whose witness is contained in are eligible, so no unsafe answer is served from the CAS.
-
(iv)
Safety invariant preserved. After re-initialization, the safety invariant holds if and only if , verified by Stage 3 applied to .
Proof.
(i) by definition. is computed by the worklist algorithm in (Definition 2.1), independent of the session history.
(ii) A PAB entry is valid under iff (Theorem 4.1). If , some required precondition has been revoked, so and the entry must be invalidated. If , then (since and is disjoint from ); by monotonicity of , , so the entry remains valid.
(iii) After re-initialization, the Stage 0 lookup condition is tested against the freshly computed . Only entries valid under are returned, so the containment guarantee of Theorem 4.1 holds.
(iv) iff , which is exactly the Stage 3 check applied to . ∎∎
Remark 10.2.
Theorem 10.1 shows that Monotonicity failure is not catastrophic: recovery costs exactly one closure recomputation plus a linear scan of the PAB. For typical deployments where revocations are rare (most sessions complete without capability loss), the amortized cost of recovery is negligible. The worst case — every turn triggers a revocation — gives total session cost , which matches the no-cache baseline and is never worse.
11 Conclusion
This paper proposes a reframing: safety certification in capability-based dialogue systems is not a gate on top of an answer pipeline. It is itself the answer pipeline. The fixed-point closure computed at certification time is the complete latent answer space for the current session configuration. The CAS+PAB architecture makes this latent space explicit and operational, eliminating redundant retrieval and generation for all queries within the session closure.
The contribution is simultaneously formal and practical. On the formal side: three families of guarantees (safety, efficiency, extraction) organized around the closure as the central primitive; a Graceful Degradation theorem that converts the Monotonicity Assumption from a fragility into a bounded recovery property; and a proof that semantic caching is structurally unsafe in multi-tenant settings. On the practical side: Algorithm 1 derives a deployable hypergraph from co-occurrence statistics automatically; the Session Cost Theorem’s prediction is confirmed at on 10,438 real human-human dialogues; and every assumption is paired with a falsifiable prediction.
The experiments on MultiWOZ 2.2 are a controlled validation of the formal model. The NatCS protocol in Appendix B defines what a validation on noisier, real-world data would look like. Running that experiment is the next step.
The safety gate is the index of the cache. The closure is the answer to every question the conversation will ask.
Appendix A Experimental Protocol for Fix C: -Incompleteness Stress Test
This appendix specifies the experiment needed to address the reviewer’s concern that the MultiWOZ evaluation uses belief states that are “complete by construction,” which means the Completeness Assumption (Definition 3.1) is never stress-tested. The experiment measures how the safety and PAB guarantees degrade when is systematically incomplete.
Design
Dataset.
Use the MultiWOZ 2.2 test split (1,000 dialogues). Ground-truth belief states serve as the “oracle” .
Incompleteness injection.
For each dialogue, randomly omit slots from the belief state with omission rate . Omission is slot-level (not value-level): if hotel-area is omitted, the capability node hotel-area-north is absent from even though the user mentioned it. This simulates a belief state tracker with recall .
Metrics.
For each omission rate , measure:
-
1.
Safety violation rate: fraction of sessions where but (the gate incorrectly passes a forbidden activation because a required capability was omitted from the assembly).
-
2.
False rejection rate: fraction of sessions where but (the gate incorrectly blocks a safe activation because an omitted capability caused a spurious forbidden path).
-
3.
PAB recall: fraction of oracle PAB entries that are also in the injected-incompleteness PAB (measures how much pre-answer coverage is lost when is incomplete).
-
4.
AND-violation rate: fraction of multi-slot turns where the hypergraph planner fires an arc with incomplete preconditions due to the missing slot.
Hypothesis.
Safety violation rate should be near zero for small (omitting a slot is more likely to block an arc than to open a forbidden one) and grow at most linearly in for the rate range tested. False rejection rate should be zero for the extracted hypergraph at (omissions do not create new arcs toward ). PAB recall should degrade smoothly, reaching approximately under independence (consistent with Theorem 4.2).
Implementation.
The experiment requires no new data: it runs entirely on the existing MultiWOZ test split with stochastic slot omission. Runtime: approximately 2 hours on a single CPU for all five omission rates. The code follows Algorithm 3 and Algorithm 1 with the injected belief states replacing the ground-truth belief states.
Expected contribution.
This experiment converts the “complete by construction” limitation from a stated assumption into a measured degradation curve. It answers: at what tracker recall does the safety guarantee materially degrade? If safety violations remain below 1% for (consistent with tracker recall on MultiWOZ, which state-of-the-art models achieve), the practical robustness of the framework is validated even under realistic tracker imperfection.
Appendix B Experimental Protocol for Appendix B: NatCS Validation
This appendix specifies the experiment that addresses the core empirical limitation of the paper: everything validated so far uses MultiWOZ belief states that are “complete by construction.” NatCS [8] provides a public corpus of spoken customer service conversations across five domains (banking, insurance, telco, retail, travel) where no belief state annotations exist. Running the pipeline on NatCS tests the full stack: belief state estimation via a pre-trained tracker, capability assembly from estimated belief states, safety gate on the assembled set, and PAB serving on follow-up turns.
Why NatCS and Not ABCD
The Action-Based Conversations Dataset (ABCD; Chen et al. 2021) is also a strong candidate. NatCS is preferred because: (a) it is drawn from real spoken interactions rather than scripted role-play; (b) its five domains provide more domain-transfer variation than ABCD’s single customer service context; and (c) it has been specifically designed to test systems in settings representative of real customer support deployments. Both datasets are public and we encourage replication on ABCD as well.
Design
Dataset.
NatCS training split for fitting the belief state tracker; NatCS test split (approximately 2,000 conversations) for evaluation. No ground-truth belief states are used in testing.
Belief state estimation.
Apply a pre-trained task-oriented dialogue state tracker (e.g., TRADE [18] fine-tuned on NatCS training split) to produce estimated belief states at each turn. The capability assembly function is .
Hypergraph extraction.
Run Algorithm 1 on the NatCS training split co-occurrence statistics at to produce . Report , , mean fan-in, fraction conjunctive, and min observed rate.
Metrics.
The primary metrics are:
-
1.
PAB hit rate: fraction of follow-up turns served from the session PAB without RAG, at TemplateDB coverage .
-
2.
Safety violation rate: fraction of sessions where the estimated belief state causes the safety gate to pass an activation that the oracle belief state would block. Measured by comparing to on a hand-labelled subsample (50 conversations, annotated by two annotators, adjudicated on disagreement).
-
3.
Session cost: mean RAG calls per session, compared to the MultiWOZ result of 1.31 and the no-cache baseline.
-
4.
AND-violation rate: fraction of multi-slot turns where the hypergraph planner fires on partial preconditions under asynchronous simulation (50 ms inter-branch latency injection).
Hypotheses.
-
1.
PAB hit rate on NatCS is within percentage points of the MultiWOZ result at matched coverage , confirming that the architecture generalizes across benchmarks.
-
2.
Safety violation rate remains below 2% under tracker recall (the minimum acceptable threshold for state-of-the-art trackers on held-out data).
-
3.
Mean RAG calls per session is in , consistent with the Session Cost Theorem prediction and the expectation that NatCS sessions have domain shifts.
-
4.
Hypergraph planner AND-violations: 0% under all conditions, consistent with Theorem 3.1.
What a failure would mean.
If PAB hit rate on NatCS falls more than 10 points below MultiWOZ, it indicates that the session closure model does not generalise from annotated benchmarks to real spoken dialogue — a meaningful limitation that would require redesigning the TemplateDB construction procedure. If safety violation rate exceeds 2%, it indicates that tracker errors propagate into safety failures at a rate inconsistent with the graceful degradation prediction of Theorem 10.1 — which would require either a tighter tracker or a more conservative . Either failure would be an informative result, not a paper-breaking one.
Implementation.
Estimated runtime: 4–6 hours on a single GPU for tracker fine-tuning, plus 2–3 hours CPU for the pipeline evaluation. No data beyond the public NatCS corpus is required. The NatCS corpus and the TRADE tracker codebase are both publicly available under permissive licences.
